```json
{
  "application": "Slurm",
  "details": {
    "job_name": "KCARTA_CO2JAC_DRIVER",
    "requeue": true,
    "matlab_instances": 1,
    "cores_per_matlab": 1,
    "partition": "high_mem",
    "qos": "short+",
    "time": "0:59:00",
    "memory_per_cpu": "8000MB",
    "matlab_commands": [
      "matlab -nodisplay -r \"clust_make_ch4_1700_2000_all; clust_make_ch4_coljac_1700_2000; clust_make_ch4_coljac_1700_2000v2; exit\"",
      "matlab -nodisplay -r \"clust_make_n2o_315_340_all; clust_make_n2o_coljac_315_340; clust_make_n2o_coljac_315_340v2; exit\""
    ]
  }
}
```

This script is designed to run on the Slurm workload manager. The script sets up a job named "KCARTA_CO2JAC_DRIVER" that will run MATLAB commands. It uses the following Slurm parameters:

* **--job-name**: Defines the name of the job.
* **--requeue**:  Enables the job to be automatically requeued if it is held.
* **-N**: Specifies the number of job steps (MATLAB instances) to be allocated.
* **--cpus-per-task**:  Sets the number of cores per MATLAB session.
* **--partition**:  Specifies the desired Slurm partition (high_mem in this case).
* **--qos**: Sets the quality of service (short+ for short jobs).
* **--time**:  Sets the maximum runtime for the job.
* **--mem-per-cpu**:  Defines the amount of memory to allocate per CPU core.
* **--array**: This parameter is not used in the script but is mentioned in the comment as a way to run multiple instances of the script.

The script then executes three MATLAB commands using the `matlab -nodisplay -r` command, which allows running MATLAB scripts without a graphical display. The specific commands are:

* **`clust_make_ch4_1700_2000_all`**: Likely a MATLAB function to create data related to methane.
* **`clust_make_ch4_coljac_1700_2000`**:  Another MATLAB function, possibly for calculating Jacobians.
* **`clust_make_ch4_coljac_1700_2000v2`**:  A possible variation of the previous function.

The script also includes comments on how to run it with an array of jobs using `sbatch --array`. This suggests that the script is likely part of a larger workflow that involves running several instances of the MATLAB commands.
